# t/web/memory-bad-name.test — a memory NAME is a slug, and a bad one is refused at
# the edge (feature-memory.md hardening). An owner-form name like `../../evil` would,
# unguarded, make WriteMemory's box path escape the sandbox and wedge EVERY future
# run's provisioning; a name with spaces/metacharacters would inject raw into the
# in/MEMORY.md index. The remember form rejects both with a field error and
# re-renders (422); nothing enters the collection; a later task still provisions and
# runs normally — proving no system-wide wedge. This also proves the form normalises
# a browser's CRLF body to LF, so an owner re-save stays byte-identical to the agent's.

send allow-sender { address kasi@decode.ee }

# A known-good fact, so we can prove a bad submit leaves the collection untouched.
memory write reply-style [fixture memory/reply-style.md]

# The poison pill: a path-traversal name. The form rejects it and re-renders with the
# slug error — the name never reaches the reducer, the model, or the workspace edge.
post /memory {
    name    ../../evil
    content [fixture memory/owner-timezone.md]
} matches "*a name may contain only*"

# A name with a space is an injection vector into the one-line-per-entry index; it is
# refused the same way. (Brackets/newlines can't even be typed as a slug — the rule
# bans every metacharacter at once.)
post /memory {
    name    bad name
    content [fixture memory/owner-timezone.md]
} matches "*a name may contain only*"

# The collection is EXACTLY what it was — no `evil`, no `bad name`, only reply-style.
visit /memory matches "*reply-style*"
memory reply-style matches "*Lead with the answer*"

# No wedge: a delivered task still provisions the collection and reaches the agent,
# then completes. A persistent poison would have failed start-agent-run here.
deliver {
    from    kasi@decode.ee
    to      research@kasi.test
    subject "pay this"
    body    "pay the attached invoice"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent
task 1 input memory/reply-style.md matches "*Lead with the answer*"
agent {
    out reply.txt "Paid."
}
task 1 status is awaiting-user

# A VALID slug still saves through the same form — the guard rejects only bad names.
post /memory {
    name    owner-timezone
    content [fixture memory/owner-timezone.md]
}
visit /memory matches "*owner-timezone*"
memory owner-timezone matches "*Europe/Berlin*"

# The owner submits a note with browser CRLF line endings; the form normalises them
# to LF and keeps the trailing newline, so the stored raw bytes are byte-identical to
# the LF note an agent would have authored (feature-memory.md: one collection, two
# interfaces, identical bytes).
post /memory {
    name    crlf-note
    content [fixture memory/crlf-note.md]
}
memory crlf-note is [fixture memory/crlf-note-lf.md]
